		<!-- message -->
		<div>I can confirm that I see the same thing Coren describes. You definitely do &quot;lose&quot; mana.<br />
<br />
Strike of Solusek costs 640 mana to cast. Say I am low on mana, and waiting to cast the final nuke to finish off a mob. As soon as I see my mana go above 640, I try to cast SoS. It says insufficient mana and reduces my mana to what it was the previous tick. I then wait for my mana to go above 640 again, cast SoS again, and get insufficient mana again, and again my mana is reduced. If I keep casting as soon as my mana goes above 640, I can stay in this state forever, without my mana ever rising above 640. As Coren says, during this time my mana should be regenerating, so if I can keep my mana under 640 without casting anything, the mana is definitely being lost.<br />
<br />
My assumption is that by casting &quot;too early&quot;, the client (your PC) thinks you have enough mana, but for some reason the server does not. The server sees this as a possible exploit and &quot;corrects&quot; the client by telling it to reset its mana count to the lower value. This isn't a matter of the client getting out of sync with the server, because I can always replicate this problem.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
